passages.text: TTV refueling - FY25 result

Guidance of 1H26 UPBT to be "fairly flat" vs pcp was at odds with our prior expectations. While TTV growth appears healthy, FLT have stepped away from providing full- year quantitative guidance with ongoing volatility and cyclical challenges continuing to be seen in early trade. Given the challenges, the company is focusing on cost discipline with benefits from GBS initiatives expected in 2H26 and a rectification of issues in Asia expected to lead to a recovery in Corporate margins. However, with valuation undemanding and our price target ahead of the current share price, we remain Overweight. PT AS15.50.

- Challenging conditions persist: Geopolitical tensions and macro-economic uncertainty continue to impact early FY26 trading. FLT have not provided detailed quantitative guidance for the full-year, but have flagged they expect 1H profits to be "fairly flat" given the cyclical challenges and the strong Q2 pcp. Given the top-line headwinds we expect cost control/out will play a big part in delivering this outcome - particularly in the context of the significant drop in profitability in 4Q25. Improved growth/performance into 2H26 appears predicated on a stabilization in the cycle and benefits felt from easing economic/geopolitical pressures (rates, etc). It is worth noting the 2% UPBT margin target in this context as well. Group PBT margins fell 10bps to 1.2% in FY25 and on the earnings call management acknowledged achievement of the 2% margin target has been delayed.

- Cash flow and balance sheet: Op. cash conversion was very weak in FY25, with GOCF coming in well below EBITDA. FLT attributed this to a significant drag from BSP payment timing of c.A\\$200m. This impact at least partially reversed in early FY26 (to the tune of c.A\\$100m) - hence, it is worth monitoring at the 1H26 result. Below the operating line, capex increased by 7% y/y. The net result of the weak cash conversion and capex increase was negative FCF of -A\\$55m (vs underlying NPAT of c.A\\$167m). Given the top-line headwinds and lingering uncertainty it is unsurprising that FLT have flagged an expected 10-15% drop in capex into FY26; and the b/s remains solid.

- Chase CardSpending Data. Following FLT's late APR guidance downgrade, Chase Card data showed no improvement in Airline spend to end FY25, down -13% in April, -7% in May, and -14% in June (rolling seven-day basis). Since Jun-25, Airline spend has improved and the gap has narrowed to -3.5% vs through to the end of July (see here for disclaimers and methodology).

- Earnings and valuation. Our earnings revisions (FY26/27 PBT -12%/-11%) reflect the company's guidance of 1H26 PBT to be fairly flat vs 1H25 PBT of \(\) 117m\(. We expect cost and productivity initiatives to lead to an improvement in margins from 2H26 onwards, while a rectification of the issues in Asia should lead to a recovery in Corporate margins. At -11x P/E, headline multiples are undemanding, however, the lack of clarity in forward bookings/ take rates remains challenging. Overweight. PT AS15.50.
Sources for: Style Exposure - J.P. Morgan Global Markets Strategy; all other tables are company data and J.P. Morgan estimates.

Flight Centre Travel Group is one of the world's largest travel agency groups; it has company- owned operations in 23 countries and a corporate travel management network that spans more than 90 countries.

Corporate TTV has recovered strongly above the market and has already exceeded pre- pandemic levels, supported by continued client wins leveraging its dual- brand strategy (i.e., FCM and Corporate Traveller). The Leisure omni- channel strategy is being executed well with market share gains in OTA and independent networks, which should support the TTV recovery of the segment. While there are some structural headwinds including airline commission cuts and supply constraints, the company has optimised its business model over the pandemic period, leading to significantly improved operating leverage prospects. We rate the stock OW.
Our Jun- 26 PT of \(15.50 is derived from our DCF valuation. Derivation and key inputs: DCF valuation: WACC 11.2%, TGR 3%.

Geopolitical tensions and macro- economic uncertainty continue to impact early FY26 trading. FLT have not provided detailed quantitative guidance for the full- year, but have flagged they expect 1H profits to be "fairly flat" given the cyclical challenges and the strong Q2 pcp. Given the top- line headwinds we expect cost control/ out will play a big part in delivering this outcome - particularly in the context of the significant drop in profitability in 4Q25. Improved growth/performance into 2H26 appears predicated on a stabilization in the cycle and benefits felt from easing economic/geopolitical pressures (rates, etc). It is worth noting the \(2\%\) UPBT margin target in this context as well.

Op. cash conversion was very weak in FY25, with GOCF coming in well below EBITDA. FLT attributed this to a significant drag from BSP payment timing of c.A\$200m. This impact has at least partially reversed in early FY26 (to the tune of c.A\$100m) - hence, worth monitoring at the 1H26 result. Below the operating line capex increased \(7\%\) y/y. Source: Company reports and J.P. Morgan estimates.
Group PBT margin fell 10bps to \(1.2\%\) in FY25 and on the earnings call management acknowledged achievement of the \(2\%\) margin target has been delayed.

Following FLT's late APR guidance downgrade, Chase Card data showed no improvement in Airline spend to end FY25, down - \(13\%\) y/y in April, \(- 7\%\) in May, and \(- 14\%\) in June (rolling seven- day basis). Since Jun- 25, Airline spend has improved and the gap has narrowed to \(- 3.5\%\) vs pcp through to the end of July.
Figure 2: Forecasted Corporate TTV and Revenue Margin A$ Millions
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates, Company data.

FLT's corporate division delivered in- line TTV (- 1% vs JPME and Cons) on stronger revenue margins ( \(9.3\%\) 1H25) given an increased contribution from the higher yielding, SME business Corporate Traveller. However, UPBT missed expectations (- 4% vs Cons), a result of a) two of FCM's largest customers down- trading over the half (pleasingly, FCM exited the period with one of these clients now returning to regular volume) and b) underperformance in Asia, whereby airfare ticket price deflation, greater regional downtrading, and a \(\) 5.2\(m provision taken out against local system changes resulted in the region printing a UPBT loss of -\) 4m UPBT loss.
Figure 4: FLT - Historical P/E
Source: Company reports and J.P. Morgan estimates.

Earnings changesFollowing the FY25 result, we adjust our earnings forecasts as outlined in the table below. Given the company's guidance of 1H26 PBT to be fairly flat vs 1H25 PBT of \(\) 117m\(, our FY26 / 27 PBT estimates have fallen - 12\% / - 11\%\). We expect cost and productivity initiatives to lead to an improvement in margins from 2H26 onwards, while a rectification of the issues in Asia should lead to a recovery in Corporate margins.
